---
/**
 * /compliance-gap — The compliance layer x402 does not ship with.
 *
 * Highest-leverage page in the BUILD_PLAN_pay_sh_response.md set.
 * Sent to Catena Labs, Circle, Bridge, Paxos for sponsor conversations.
 *
 * Frame: x402 specifies the protocol; the regulated counterparty layer is
 * unspecified by design. pay.sh demonstrates this gap at scale. Stable402
 * names the four legs where regulatory questions live, and the named
 * industry players who can answer them.
 *
 * Voice matches /cloudflare and /pay-sh: declarative, named-vendor,
 * honesty-marker conventions. No fluff. No legal advice — descriptive only.
 *
 * NOTE: This page describes the regulatory landscape; it is not legal
 * advice. The closing footer says so explicitly.
 *
 * TODO: Phase B may add hover tooltips to the four-leg diagram nodes.
 * If so, follow the canonical tooltip standard in CLAUDE.md / Atlas
 * Production Spec §4.2.
 */
import Main from '../layouts/Main.astro';
---

<Main
  title="The compliance layer x402 does not ship with — Stable402"
  description="x402 specifies the protocol; the regulated counterparty layer is unspecified by design. The four legs of an agent-payments flow each carry a regulatory question. This is where they live and who can answer them."
>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       HERO
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section class="cg-hero">
    <p class="cg-eyebrow">Compliance reference · 2026-05-07</p>
    <h1>The compliance layer x402 <span class="cg-accent">doesn't ship with</span>.</h1>
    <p class="cg-subhead">
      x402 specifies the protocol — the HTTP 402 challenge, the payment proof,
      the facilitator handshake. The <strong>regulated counterparty layer</strong> is
      unspecified by design. <a href="/pay-sh">pay.sh</a> demonstrates this gap at scale:
      Solana Foundation and Google Cloud shipped a production gateway with one sentence
      addressing compliance. The four legs of any agent-payments flow each carry a
      regulatory question. This page names them, and names the industry players who can
      answer them.
    </p>

    <p class="cg-honesty">
      <strong>What this page is.</strong> A descriptive map of where regulatory questions
      live in an x402 flow, written for compliance officers, fintech program leads, and
      acquirers doing due diligence on agent payments. <strong>What it is not.</strong>
      Legal or regulatory advice. The named industry players are illustrative of who
      <em>can</em> hold each role — actual licensing posture and jurisdictional coverage
      are matters for the parties themselves to confirm.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       SECTION 1: THE FOUR-LEG FLOW DIAGRAM
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section class="cg-section">
    <p class="cg-section-eyebrow">Section 1</p>
    <h2 class="cg-section-title">The four legs.</h2>
    <p class="cg-section-body">
      An agent-to-API payment over x402 has four loci where a regulatory obligation
      lands. The diagram below is the canonical flow — agent wallet pays a facilitator,
      which authorizes and settles to an API provider, which receives fiat through a
      separate off-ramp leg. Each box names the regulatory question that has to be
      answered before that leg goes to production volume.
    </p>

    <div class="cg-flow">
